# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: uav-flight-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An **accelerometer** is a device that measures the proper acceleration of an object.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is the acceleration (the rate of change of velocity) of the object relative to an observer who is in free fall (that is, relative to an inertial frame of reference).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Proper acceleration is different from coordinate acceleration, which is acceleration with respect to a given coordinate system, which may or may not be accelerating.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] For example, an accelerometer at rest on the surface of the Earth will measure an acceleration due to Earth's gravity straight upwards of about *g* ≈ 9.81 m/s2.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] By contrast, an accelerometer that is in free fall will measure zero acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Highly sensitive accelerometers are used in inertial navigation systems for aircraft and missiles.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In unmanned aerial vehicles, accelerometers help to stabilize flight.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Micromachined micro-electromechanical systems (MEMS) accelerometers are used in handheld electronic devices such as smartphones, cameras and video-game controllers to detect movement and orientation of these devices.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Vibration in industrial machinery is monitored by accelerometers.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Seismometers are sensitive accelerometers for monitoring ground movement such as earthquakes.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] When two or more accelerometers are coordinated with one another, they can measure differences in proper acceleration, particularly gravity, over their separation in space—that is, the gradient of the gravitational field.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Gravity gradiometry is useful because absolute gravity is a weak effect and depends on the local density of the Earth, which is quite variable.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A single-axis accelerometer measures acceleration along a specified axis.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A multi-axis accelerometer detects both the magnitude and the direction of the proper acceleration, as a vector quantity, and is usually implemented as several single-axis accelerometers oriented along different axes.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An accelerometer measures proper acceleration, which is the acceleration it experiences relative to freefall and is the acceleration felt by people and objects.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Put another way, at any point in spacetime the equivalence principle guarantees the existence of a local inertial frame, and an accelerometer measures the acceleration relative to that frame.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Such accelerations are popularly denoted g-force; i.e., in comparison to standard gravity.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An accelerometer at rest relative to the Earth's surface will indicate approximately 1 g *upwards* because the Earth's surface exerts a normal force upwards relative to the local inertial frame (the frame of a freely falling object near the surface).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] To obtain the acceleration due to motion with respect to the Earth, this "gravity offset" must be subtracted and corrections made for effects caused by the Earth's rotation relative to the inertial frame.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The reason for the appearance of a gravitational offset is Einstein's equivalence principle, which states that the effects of gravity on an object are indistinguishable from acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] When held fixed in a gravitational field by, for example, applying a ground reaction force or an equivalent upward thrust, the reference frame for an accelerometer (its own casing) accelerates upwards with respect to a free-falling reference frame.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] For similar reasons, an accelerometer will read *zero* during any type of free fall.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This includes use in a coasting spaceship in deep space far from any mass, a spaceship orbiting the Earth, an airplane in a parabolic "zero-g" arc, or any free-fall in a vacuum.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Another example is free-fall at a sufficiently high altitude that atmospheric effects can be neglected.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] However, this does not include a (non-free) fall in which air resistance produces drag forces that reduce the acceleration until constant terminal velocity is reached.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] At terminal velocity, the accelerometer will indicate 1 g acceleration upwards.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] For the same reason a skydiver, upon reaching terminal velocity, does not feel as though he or she were in "free-fall", but rather experiences a feeling similar to being supported (at 1 g) on a "bed" of uprushing air.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Acceleration is quantified in the SI unit metres per second per second (m/s2), in the cgs unit gal (Gal), or popularly in terms of standard gravity (*g*).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] For the practical purpose of finding the acceleration of objects with respect to the Earth, such as for use in an inertial navigation system, a knowledge of local gravity is required.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This can be obtained either by calibrating the device at rest, or from a known model of gravity at the approximate current position.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A basic mechanical accelerometer is a damped proof mass on a spring.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] When the accelerometer experiences an acceleration, Newton's third law causes the spring's compression (or extension) to adjust to exert an equivalent force on the mass to counteract the acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Since the spring's force scales linearly with the length change (according to Hooke's law) and because the spring constant and mass are known constants, a measurement of the spring's compression (or extension) is also a measurement of acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The system is damped to prevent oscillations of the mass and spring interfering with measurements.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] However, the damping causes accelerometers to have a frequency response.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Many animals have sensory organs to detect acceleration, especially gravity.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In these, the proof mass is usually one or more crystals of calcium carbonate otoliths (Latin for "ear stone") or statoconia, acting against a bed of hairs connected to neurons.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The hairs form the springs, with the neurons as sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Many vertebrates, including humans, have these structures in their inner ears.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Most invertebrates have similar organs, but not as part of their hearing organs.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Mechanical accelerometers are often designed so that an electronic circuit senses a small amount of motion, then pushes on the proof mass with some type of linear motor to keep the proof mass from moving far.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The motor might be an electromagnet or in very small accelerometers, electrostatic.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Since the circuit's electronic behavior can be carefully designed, and the proof mass does not move far, these designs can be very stable (i.e. they do not oscillate), very linear with a controlled frequency response.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In mechanical accelerometers, measurement is often electrical, piezoelectric, piezoresistive or capacitive.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers use piezoceramic sensors (e.g. lead zirconate titanate) or single crystals (e.g. quartz, tourmaline).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] They are unmatched in high frequency measurements, low packaged weight, and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Piezoresistive accelerometers resist shock (very high accelerations) better.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Capacitive accelerometers typically use a silicon micro-machined sensing element.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Modern mechanical accelerometers are often small *micro-electro-mechanical systems* (MEMS), and are often very simple MEMS devices, consisting of little more than a cantilever beam with a proof mass (also known as *seismic mass*).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Damping results from the residual gas sealed in the device.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] As long as the Q-factor is not too low, damping does not result in a lower sensitivity.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Under the influence of external accelerations, the proof mass deflects from its neutral position.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This deflection is measured in an analog or digital manner.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Most commonly, the capacitance between a set of fixed beams and a set of beams attached to the proof mass is measured.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This method is simple, reliable, and inexpensive.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Integrating piezoresistors in the springs to detect spring deformation, and thus deflection, is a good alternative, although a few more process steps are needed during the fabrication sequence.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] For very high sensitivities quantum tunnelling is also used; this requires a dedicated process making it very expensive.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Optical measurement has been demonstrated in laboratory devices.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Another MEMS-based accelerometer is a thermal (or convective) accelerometer.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] It contains a small heater in a very small dome.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This heats the air or other fluid inside the dome.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The thermal bubble acts as the proof mass.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An accompanying temperature sensor (like a thermistor; or thermopile) in the dome measures the temperature in one location of the dome.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This measures the location of the heated bubble within the dome.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] When the dome is accelerated, the colder, higher density fluid pushes the heated bubble.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The temperature measurement is interpreted as acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Gravity acting on the fluid provides the spring.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Since the proof mass is very lightweight gas, and not held by a beam or lever, thermal accelerometers can survive high shocks.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Another variation uses a wire to both heat the gas and detect the change in temperature.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The change of temperature changes the resistance of the wire.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A two dimensional accelerometer can be economically constructed with one dome, one bubble and two measurement devices.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Most micromechanical accelerometers operate *in-plane*, that is, they are designed to be sensitive only to a direction in the plane of the die.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] By integrating two devices perpendicularly on a single die a two-axis accelerometer can be made.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] By adding another *out-of-plane* device, three axes can be measured.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Such a combination may have much lower misalignment error than three discrete models combined after packaging.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Micromechanical accelerometers are available in a wide variety of measuring ranges, reaching up to thousands of *g*'s.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The designer must compromise between sensitivity and the maximum acceleration that can be measured.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vehicle acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers can be used to measure vibration on cars, machines, buildings, process control systems and safety installations.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] They can also be used to measure seismic activity, inclination, machine vibration, dynamic distance and speed with or without the influence of gravity.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Applications for accelerometers that measure gravity, wherein an accelerometer is specifically configured for use in gravimetry, are called gravimeters.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also increasingly used in the biological sciences.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] High frequency recordings of bi-axial or tri-axial acceleration allows the discrimination of behavioral patterns while animals are out of sight.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] For example, accelerometers have been used to study flight energy expenditure of Harris's Hawk (*Parabuteo unicinctus*).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Researchers are also using smartphone accelerometers to collect and extract mechano-biological descriptors of resistance exercise.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Increasingly, researchers are deploying accelerometers with additional technology, such as cameras or microphones, to better understand animal behaviour in the wild (for example, hunting behaviour of Canada lynx).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also used for machinery health monitoring to report the vibration and its changes in time of shafts at the bearings of rotating equipment such as turbines, pumps, fans, rollers, compressors, or bearing fault which, if not attended to promptly, can lead to costly repairs.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometer vibration data allows the user to monitor machines and detect these faults before the rotating equipment fails completely.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are widely used in structural health monitoring (SHM) of buildings, bridges and other civil infrastructure to record the dynamic response under ambient and forced loads (e.g., wind, traffic, machinery and earthquakes).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] From these vibration records, engineers estimate modal properties—natural frequencies, damping ratios and mode shapes—often using operational modal analysis (OMA) techniques for in-service structures.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] These parameters are trended over time for condition assessment and model updating.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In seismic regions, arrays of accelerometers installed in buildings and other structures provide strong-motion data for rapid post-event assessments and long-term performance studies.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Geological Survey's National Strong-Motion Project (NSMP) operates structural arrays and distributes building and structural records via the Center for Engineering Strong Motion Data (CESMD).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Instrumentation and data-quality practices for building vibration measurements are guided by international standards.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] ISO 4866 provides principles for measuring the vibration of fixed structures and evaluating vibration effects based on structural response, while ISO 10137 gives serviceability recommendations for buildings and walkways with respect to human perception, contents and the structure itself.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Choice of accelerometer technology depends on frequency range and amplitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Piezoelectric accelerometers are common for higher-frequency, higher-amplitude measurements, whereas low-noise MEMS accelerometers have become attractive for low-frequency building and bridge monitoring and for dense or wireless deployments due to cost and power advantages.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Recent evaluations and developments show that appropriately selected MEMS devices can identify modal parameters with acceptable accuracy for SHM and have been integrated into high-sensitivity wireless nodes.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Networked and wireless smart-sensor approaches allow distributed monitoring at scale.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Reviews document the shift from wired to wireless SHM systems and the maturation of wireless smart-sensor networks for tasks such as ambient-vibration modal identification and continuous trending.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are often fused with other sensors to improve displacement and drift estimation, especially for large or flexible structures.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] GNSS provides quasi-static and very-low-frequency motion that complements accelerometer-based dynamics; recent studies report accurate dynamic displacement retrieval using high-rate or multi-GNSS solutions combined with accelerometers.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Beyond permanently instrumented assets, indirect and crowdsourced approaches using smartphone accelerometers have been explored, particularly for bridges.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Research has shown that modal frequencies—and in some cases spatial vibration characteristics—can be estimated from accelerometer data collected by vehicles crossing bridges, offering a complementary, low-cost screening tool for large inventories.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Related work has also evaluated smartphone-based ambient vibration monitoring of buildings.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Long-term case studies illustrate large-scale deployments.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Hong Kong's Wind and Structural Health Monitoring System (WASHMS) has instrumented the Tsing Ma Bridge since 1997; subsequent publications report decades of monitoring for load and response in service.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Scotland's Queensferry Crossing was equipped with a comprehensive SHM system including thousands of sensors, and Sydney Harbour Bridge has been reported as instrumented with thousands of sensors for real-time monitoring.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] SHM data are used for continuous condition tracking, event-triggered assessments (e.g., after earthquakes), and to support asset management decisions.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In bridge engineering, guidance from transportation agencies describes how field data—including accelerometer measurements—can be integrated with inspection and nondestructive evaluation to improve load-rating reliability and maintenance planning.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Zoll's AED Plus uses CPR-D•padz which contain an accelerometer to measure the depth of CPR chest compressions.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Within the last several years, several companies have produced and marketed sports watches for runners that include footpods, containing accelerometers to help determine the speed and distance for the runner wearing the unit.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In Belgium, accelerometer-based step counters are promoted by the government to encourage people to walk a few thousand steps each day.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Herman Digital Trainer uses accelerometers to measure strike force in physical training.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] It has been suggested to build football helmets with accelerometers in order to measure the impact of head collisions.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The US Army Research Laboratory developed the Three-Axis Acceleration Switch which has been suggested for this application.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers have been used to calculate gait parameters, such as stance and swing phase.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This kind of sensor can be used to measure or monitor people.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An inertial navigation system is a navigation aid that uses a computer and motion sensors (accelerometers) to continuously calculate via dead reckoning the position, orientation, and velocity (direction and speed of movement) of a moving object without the need for external references.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Other terms used to refer to inertial navigation systems or closely related devices include inertial guidance system, inertial reference platform, and many other variations.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An accelerometer alone is unsuitable to determine changes in altitude over distances where the vertical decrease of gravity is significant, such as for aircraft and rockets.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In the presence of a gravitational gradient, the calibration and data reduction process is numerically unstable.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used to detect apogee in both professional and in amateur rocketry.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are also being used in Intelligent Compaction rollers.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used alongside gyroscopes in inertial navigation systems.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] One of the most common uses for MEMS accelerometers is in airbag deployment systems for modern automobiles.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In this case, the accelerometers are used to detect the rapid negative acceleration of the vehicle to determine when a collision has occurred and the severity of the collision.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Another common automotive use is in electronic stability control systems, which use a lateral accelerometer to measure cornering forces.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The widespread use of accelerometers in the automotive industry has pushed their cost down dramatically.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Another automotive application is the monitoring of noise, vibration, and harshness (NVH), conditions that cause discomfort for drivers and passengers and may also be indicators of mechanical faults.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Tilting trains use accelerometers and gyroscopes to calculate the required tilt.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Modern electronic accelerometers are used in remote sensing devices intended for the monitoring of active volcanoes to detect the motion of magma.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are increasingly being incorporated into personal electronic devices to detect the orientation of the device, for example, a display screen.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A *free-fall sensor* (FFS) is an accelerometer used to detect if a system has been dropped and is falling.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] It can then apply safety measures such as parking the head of a hard disk to prevent a head crash and resulting data loss upon impact.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This device is included in the many common computer and consumer electronic products that are produced by a variety of manufacturers.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] It is also used in some data loggers to monitor handling operations for shipping containers.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The length of time in free fall is used to calculate the height of drop and to estimate the shock to the package.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Some smartphones, digital audio players and personal digital assistants contain accelerometers for user interface control; often the accelerometer is used to present landscape or portrait views of the device's screen, based on the way the device is being held.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Apple has included an accelerometer in every generation of iPhone, iPad, and iPod touch, as well as in every iPod nano since the 4th generation.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Along with orientation view adjustment, accelerometers in mobile devices can also be used as pedometers, in conjunction with specialized applications.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Automatic Collision Notification (ACN) systems also use accelerometers in a system to call for help in event of a vehicle crash.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Prominent ACN systems include OnStar AACN service, Ford Link's 911 Assist, Toyota's Safety Connect, Lexus Link, or BMW Assist.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Many accelerometer-equipped smartphones also have ACN software available for download.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] ACN systems are activated by detecting crash-strength accelerations.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Accelerometers are used in vehicle Electronic stability control systems to measure the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A computer compares the vehicle's actual movement to the driver's steering and throttle input.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The stability control computer can selectively brake individual wheels and/or reduce engine power to minimize the difference between driver input and the vehicle's actual movement.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This can help prevent the vehicle from spinning or rolling over.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Some pedometers use an accelerometer to more accurately measure the number of steps taken and distance traveled than a mechanical sensor can provide.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Nintendo's Wii video game console uses a controller called a Wii Remote that contains a three-axis accelerometer and was designed primarily for motion input.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Users also have the option of buying an additional motion-sensitive attachment, the Nunchuk, so that motion input could be recorded from both of the user's hands independently.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Is also used on the Nintendo 3DS system.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Sleep phase alarm clocks use accelerometric sensors to detect movement of a sleeper, so that it can wake the person when he/she is not in REM phase, in order to awaken the person more easily.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A microphone or eardrum is a membrane that responds to oscillations in air pressure.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] These oscillations cause acceleration, so accelerometers can be used to record sound.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A 2012 study found that voices can be detected in 93% of typical daily situations by accelerometers like those in smartphones fixed to the sternum.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Conversely, carefully designed sounds can cause accelerometers to report false data.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] One study tested 20 models of (MEMS) smartphone accelerometers and found that a majority were susceptible to this attack.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A number of 21st-century devices use accelerometers to align the screen depending on the direction the device is held (e.g., switching between portrait and landscape modes).
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Such devices include many tablet PCs and some smartphones and digital cameras.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The Amida Simputer, a handheld Linux device launched in 2004, was the first commercial handheld to have a built-in accelerometer.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] It incorporated many gesture-based interactions using this accelerometer, including page-turning, zoom-in and zoom-out of images, change of portrait to landscape mode, and many simple gesture-based games.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] As of January 2009, almost all new mobile phones and digital cameras contain at least a tilt sensor and sometimes an accelerometer for the purpose of auto image rotation, motion-sensitive mini-games, and correcting shake when taking photographs.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Camcorders use accelerometers for image stabilization, either by moving optical elements to adjust the light path to the sensor to cancel out unintended motions or digitally shifting the image to smooth out detected motion.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Some stills cameras use accelerometers for anti-blur capturing.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The camera holds off capturing the image when the camera is moving.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] When the camera is still (if only for a millisecond, as could be the case for vibration), the image is captured.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] An example of the application of this technology is the Glogger VS2, a phone application which runs on Symbian based phones with accelerometers such as the Nokia N96.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Some digital cameras contain accelerometers to determine the orientation of the photo being taken and also for rotating the current picture when viewing.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Many laptops feature an accelerometer which is used to detect drops.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] If a drop is detected, the heads of the hard disk are parked to avoid data loss and possible head or disk damage by the ensuing shock.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A gravimeter, or gravitometer, is an instrument used in gravimetry for measuring the local gravitational field.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] A gravimeter is a type of accelerometer, except that accelerometers are susceptible to all vibrations including noise, that cause oscillatory accelerations.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] This is counteracted in the gravimeter by integral vibration isolation and signal processing.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Though the essential principle of design is the same as in accelerometers, gravimeters are typically designed to be much more sensitive than accelerometers in order to measure very tiny changes within the Earth's gravity, of 1 *g*.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] In contrast, other accelerometers are often designed to measure 1000 *g* or more, and many perform multi-axial measurements.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] The constraints on temporal resolution are usually less for gravimeters, so that resolution can be increased by processing the output with a longer "time constant".
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] If done without a user's knowledge or consent, this is referred to as an inference attack.
[src:uav-flight-control/accelerometer] Additionally, millions of smartphones could be vulnerable to software cracking via accelerometers.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Controlling vehicle attitude requires actuators to apply the torques needed to orient the vehicle to a desired attitude, and algorithms to command the actuators based on the current attitude and specification of a desired attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Before and during attitude control can be performed, **spacecraft attitude determination** must be performed, which requires sensors for absolute or relative measurement.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The broader integrated field that studies the combination of sensors, actuators and algorithms is called *guidance, navigation and control*, which also involves non-attitude concepts, such as position determination and navigation.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Spacecraft generally have an attitude determination and control system (ADCS), which includes both sensors and actuators.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] However, budget satellites (such as some cubesats), may elect for simpler attitude control systems (ACS) which use passive techniques, including the yo-yo de-spin technique and permanent magnets to control the attitude of the satellite.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A spacecraft's attitude must typically be stabilized and controlled for a variety of reasons.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Many spacecraft have components that require articulation or pointing.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Voyager and *Galileo*, for example, were designed with scan platforms for pointing optical instruments at their targets largely independently of spacecraft orientation.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Many spacecraft, such as Mars orbiters, have solar panels that must track the Sun so they can provide electrical power to the spacecraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] *Cassini*'s main engine nozzles were steerable.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Knowing where to point a solar panel, or scan platform, or a nozzle — that is, how to articulate it — requires knowledge of the spacecraft's attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Because a single subsystem keeps track of the spacecraft's attitude, the Sun's location, and Earth's location, it can compute the proper direction to point the appendages.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] It logically falls to the same subsystem – the Attitude and Articulation Control Subsystem (AACS), then, to manage both attitude and articulation.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The name AACS may even be carried over to a spacecraft even if it has no appendages to articulate.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Attitude is part of the description of how an object is placed in the space it occupies.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Attitude and position fully describe how an object is placed in space.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] For some applications (e.g., robotics, computer vision), it is customary to combine position and attitude together into a single description known as Pose.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Attitude can be described using a variety of methods; however, the most common are Rotation matrices, Quaternions, and Euler angles.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] While Euler angles are oftentimes the most straightforward representation to visualize, they can cause problems for highly-maneuverable systems because of a phenomenon known as Gimbal lock.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A rotation matrix, on the other hand, provides a full description of the attitude at the expense of requiring nine values instead of three.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The use of a rotation matrix can lead to increased computational expense and they can be more difficult to work with.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Quaternions offer a decent compromise in that they do not suffer from gimbal lock and only require four values to fully describe the attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Attitude control of spacecraft is maintained using one of two principal approaches: spin stabilization and three-axis stabilization.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Spin stabilization is accomplished by setting the spacecraft spinning, using the gyroscopic action of the rotating spacecraft mass as the stabilizing mechanism.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Propulsion system thrusters are fired only occasionally to make desired changes in spin rate, or in the spin-stabilized attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] If desired, the spinning may be stopped through the use of thrusters or by yo-yo de-spin.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The *Pioneer 10* and *Pioneer 11* probes in the outer Solar System are examples of spin-stabilized spacecraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Three-axis stabilization is an alternative method of spacecraft attitude control in which the spacecraft is held fixed in the desired orientation without any rotation.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] There are advantages and disadvantages to both spin stabilization and three-axis stabilization.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Three-axis controlled craft can point optical instruments and antennas without having to de-spin them, but they may have to carry out special rotating maneuvers to best utilize their fields and particle instruments.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] If thrusters are used for routine stabilization, optical observations such as imaging must be designed knowing that the spacecraft is always slowly rocking back and forth, and not always exactly predictably.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Vernier thrusters are the most common actuators, as they may be used for station keeping as well.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Thrusters must be organized as a system to provide stabilization about all three axes, and at least two thrusters are generally used in each axis to provide torque as a couple in order to prevent imparting a translation to the vehicle.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Their limitations are fuel usage, engine wear, and cycles of the control valves.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The fuel efficiency of an attitude control system is determined by its specific impulse (proportional to exhaust velocity) and the smallest torque impulse it can provide (which determines how often the thrusters must fire to provide precise control).
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Thrusters must be fired in one direction to start rotation, and again in the opposing direction if a new orientation is to be held.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Thruster systems have been used on most crewed space vehicles, including Vostok, Mercury, Gemini, Apollo, Soyuz, and the Space Shuttle.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] To minimize the fuel limitation on mission duration, auxiliary attitude control systems may be used to reduce vehicle rotation to lower levels, such as small ion thrusters that accelerate ionized gases electrically to extreme velocities, using power from solar cells.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Momentum wheels are electric motor driven rotors made to spin in the direction opposite to that required to re-orient the vehicle.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Because momentum wheels make up a small fraction of the spacecraft's mass and are computer controlled, they give precise control.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Momentum wheels are generally suspended on magnetic bearings to avoid bearing friction and breakdown problems.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Spacecraft Reaction wheels often use mechanical ball bearings.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] To maintain orientation in three dimensional space a minimum of three reaction wheels must be used, with additional units providing single failure protection.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] These are rotors spun at constant speed, mounted on gimbals to provide attitude control.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Although a CMG provides control about the two axes orthogonal to the gyro spin axis, triaxial control still requires two units.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A CMG is a bit more expensive in terms of cost and mass, because gimbals and their drive motors must be provided.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The maximum torque (but not the maximum angular momentum change) exerted by a CMG is greater than for a momentum wheel, making it better suited to large spacecraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A major drawback is the additional complexity, which increases the number of failure points.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] For this reason, the International Space Station uses a set of four CMGs to provide dual failure tolerance.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Small solar sails (devices that produce thrust as a reaction force induced by reflecting incident light) may be used to make small attitude control and velocity adjustments.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This application can save large amounts of fuel on a long-duration mission by producing control moments without fuel expenditure.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] For example, *Mariner 10* adjusted its attitude using its solar cells and antennas as small solar sails.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] In orbit, a spacecraft with one axis much longer than the other two will spontaneously orient so that its long axis points at the planet's center of mass.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This system has the virtue of needing no active control system or expenditure of fuel.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The upper end of the vehicle feels less gravitational pull than the lower end.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This provides a restoring torque whenever the long axis is not co-linear with the direction of gravity.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Unless some means of damping is provided, the spacecraft will oscillate about the local vertical.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Sometimes tethers are used to connect two parts of a satellite, to increase the stabilizing torque.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A problem with such tethers is that meteoroids as small as a grain of sand can part them.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Coils or (on very small satellites) permanent magnets exert a moment against the local magnetic field.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This method works only where there is a magnetic field against which to react.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] One classic field "coil" is actually in the form of a conductive tether in a planetary magnetic field.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Such a conductive tether can also generate electrical power, at the expense of orbital decay.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Conversely, by inducing a counter-current, using solar cell power, the orbit may be raised.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Due to massive variability in Earth's magnetic field from an ideal radial field, control laws based on torques coupling to this field will be highly non-linear.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Moreover, only two-axis control is available at any given time meaning that a vehicle reorient may be necessary to null all rates.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Three main types of passive attitude control exist for satellites.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The first one uses gravity gradient, and it leads to four stable states with the long axis (axis with smallest moment of inertia) pointing towards Earth.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] As this system has four stable states, if the satellite has a preferred orientation, e.g. a camera pointed at the planet, some way to flip the satellite and its tether end-for-end is needed.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The second passive system orients the satellite along Earth's magnetic field thanks to a magnet.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] These purely passive attitude control systems have limited pointing accuracy, because the spacecraft will oscillate around energy minima.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This drawback is overcome by adding damper, which can be hysteretic materials or a viscous damper.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The viscous damper is a small can or tank of fluid mounted in the spacecraft, possibly with internal baffles to increase internal friction.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Friction within the damper will gradually convert oscillation energy into heat dissipated within the viscous damper.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A third form of passive attitude control is aerodynamic stabilization.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This is achieved using a drag gradient, as demonstrated on the Get Away Special Passive Attitude Control Satellite (GASPACS) technology demonstration.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] In low Earth orbit, the force due to drag is many orders of magnitude more dominant than the force imparted due to gravity gradients.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] When a satellite is utilizing aerodynamic passive attitude control, air molecules from the Earth's upper atmosphere strike the satellite in such a way that the center of pressure remains behind the center of mass, similar to how the feathers on an arrow stabilize the arrow.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] GASPACS utilized a 1 m inflatable 'AeroBoom', which extended behind the satellite, creating a stabilizing torque along the satellite's velocity vector.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Another form of passive attitude control is yo-yo de-spin.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Yo-yo de-spin devices are controversial as they generate space debris, and are primarily used for deep-space spacecraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Control algorithms are computer programs that receive data from vehicle sensors and derive the appropriate commands to the actuators to rotate the vehicle to the desired attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The algorithms range from very simple, e.g. proportional control, to complex nonlinear estimators or many in-between types, depending on mission requirements.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Typically, the attitude control algorithms are part of the software running on the computer hardware, which receives commands from the ground and formats vehicle data telemetry for transmission to a ground station.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The attitude control algorithms are written and implemented based on requirement for a particular attitude maneuver.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Asides the implementation of passive attitude control such as the gravity-gradient stabilization, most spacecraft make use of active control which exhibits a typical attitude control loop.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The design of the control algorithm depends on the actuator to be used for the specific attitude maneuver although using a simple *proportional–integral–derivative controller* (*PID controller*) satisfies most control needs.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The appropriate commands to the actuators are obtained based on error signals described as the difference between the measured and desired attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The error signals are commonly measured as euler angles (Φ, θ, Ψ), however an alternative to this could be described in terms of direction cosine matrix or error quaternions.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] where $T_{c}$ is the control torque, e is the attitude deviation signal, and $K_{\text{p}},K_{\text{i}},K_{\text{d}}$ are the PID controller parameters.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A simple implementation of this can be the application of the proportional control for nadir pointing making use of either momentum or reaction wheels as actuators.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This control algorithm also affects momentum dumping.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Another important and common control algorithm involves the concept of detumbling, which is attenuating the angular momentum of the spacecraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The need to detumble the spacecraft arises from the uncontrollable state after release from the launch vehicle.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Most spacecraft in low Earth orbit (LEO) makes use of magnetic detumbling concept which utilizes the effect of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The control algorithm is called the B-Dot controller and relies on magnetic coils or torque rods as control actuators.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The control law is based on the measurement of the rate of change of body-fixed magnetometer signals.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] where m is the commanded magnetic dipole moment of the magnetic torquer and K is the proportional gain and ${\dot {B}}$ is the rate of change of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A spacecraft's ADCS system generally begins detumbling at the start of the mission, either autonomously or when commanded.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Nadir pointing mode and sun pointing mode, among others, are implemented by using actuators to put the spacecraft into a Y-Thomson spin, named after William T.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Thomson, whereby the spacecraft completes one full rotation about its orbit normal axis as it completes one full revolution about the primary body.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] In a geocentric satellite, a Y-Thomson spin is often used to point one face of the spacecraft to face the center of gravity of the Earth.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This spin aligns the spacecraft body frame with the orbit's tangent-normal-radial reference frame.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] When combined with a nadir-pointing deployable boom, gravity-gradient forces passively stabilize the spacecraft's attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Many sensors generate outputs that reflect the rate of change in attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] These require a known initial attitude, or external information to use them to determine attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Many of this class of sensor have some noise, leading to inaccuracies if not corrected by absolute attitude sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Gyroscopes are devices that sense rotation in three-dimensional space without reliance on the observation of external objects.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Classically, a gyroscope consists of a spinning mass, but there are also "ring laser gyros" utilizing coherent light reflected around a closed path.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Another type of "gyro" is a hemispherical resonator gyro where a crystal cup shaped like a wine glass can be driven into oscillation just as a wine glass "sings" as a finger is rubbed around its rim.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] The orientation of the oscillation is fixed in inertial space, so measuring the orientation of the oscillation relative to the spacecraft can be used to sense the motion of the spacecraft with respect to inertial space.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Motion reference units are a kind of inertial measurement unit with single- or multi-axis motion sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Some multi-axis MRUs are capable of measuring roll, pitch, yaw and heave.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This class of sensors sense the position or orientation of fields, objects or other phenomena outside the spacecraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A *horizon sensor* is an optical instrument that detects light from the 'limb' of Earth's atmosphere, i.e., at the horizon.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Thermal infrared sensing is often used, which senses the comparative warmth of the atmosphere, compared to the much colder cosmic background.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This sensor provides orientation with respect to Earth about two orthogonal axes.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] It tends to be less precise than sensors based on stellar observation.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Sometimes referred to as an Earth sensor.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Thus, the horizon sensor provides pitch and roll measurements, and the gyro provides yaw.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A *Sun sensor* is a device that senses the direction to the Sun.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This can be as simple as some solar cells and shades, or as complex as a steerable telescope, depending on mission requirements.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] An *Earth sensor* is a device that senses the direction to Earth.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] It is usually an infrared camera; nowadays the main method to detect attitude is the star tracker, but Earth sensors are still integrated in satellites for their low cost and reliability.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A *star tracker* is an optical device that measures the position(s) of star(s) using photocell(s) or a camera.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] It uses magnitude of brightness and spectral type to identify and then calculate the relative position of stars around it.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] A *magnetometer* is a device that senses magnetic field strength and, when used in a three-axis triad, magnetic field direction.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] As a spacecraft navigational aid, sensed field strength and direction is compared to a map of Earth's magnetic field stored in the memory of an on-board or ground-based guidance computer.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] If spacecraft position is known then attitude can be inferred.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Attitude cannot be measured directly by any single measurement, and so must be calculated (or estimated) from a set of measurements (often using different sensors).
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Static attitude estimation methods are solutions to Wahba's problem.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Many solutions have been proposed, notably Davenport's q-method, QUEST, TRIAD, and singular value decomposition.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Kalman filtering can be used to sequentially estimate the attitude, as well as the angular rate.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Because attitude dynamics (combination of rigid body dynamics and attitude kinematics) are non-linear, a linear Kalman filter is not sufficient.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Because attitude dynamics is not very non-linear, the Extended Kalman filter is usually sufficient (however Crassidis and Markely demonstrated that the Unscented Kalman filter could be used, and can provide benefits in cases where the initial estimate is poor).
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] Multiple methods have been proposed, however the Multiplicative Extended Kalman Filter (MEKF) is by far the most common approach.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This approach utilizes the multiplicative formulation of the error quaternion, which allows for the unity constraint on the quaternion to be better handled.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] It is also common to use a technique known as dynamic model replacement, where the angular rate is not estimated directly, but rather the measured angular rate from the gyro is used directly to propagate the rotational dynamics forward in time.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This is valid for most applications as gyros are typically far more precise than one's knowledge of disturbance torques acting on the system (which is required for precise estimation of the angular rate).
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] For some sensors and applications (such as spacecraft using magnetometers) the precise location must also be known.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] While pose estimation can be employed, for spacecraft it is usually sufficient to estimate the position (via Orbit determination) separate from the attitude estimation.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] For terrestrial vehicles and spacecraft operating near the Earth, the advent of Satellite navigation systems allows for precise position knowledge to be obtained easily.
[src:uav-flight-control/attitude-control] This problem becomes more complicated for deep space vehicles, or terrestrial vehicles operating in Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) denied environments (see Navigation).
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] In aircraft flight dynamics, for a fixed-wing aircraft, its changing orientation with respect to the local air flow is represented by two critical angles, the angle of attack of the wing ("alpha") and the angle of attack of the vertical tail, known as the sideslip angle ("beta").
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] A sideslip angle will arise if an aircraft yaws about its centre of gravity and if the aircraft sideslips bodily, i.e. the centre of gravity moves sideways.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] These angles are important because they are the principal sources of changes in the aerodynamic forces and moments applied to the aircraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] Spacecraft flight dynamics involve three main forces: propulsive (rocket engine), gravitational, and atmospheric resistance.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] Propulsive force and atmospheric resistance have significantly less influence over a given spacecraft compared to gravitational forces.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] Flight dynamics is the science of air-vehicle orientation and control in three dimensions.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] The critical flight dynamics parameters are the angles of rotation with respect to the three aircraft's principal axes about its center of gravity, known as *roll*, *pitch* and *yaw*.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] Aircraft engineers develop control systems for a vehicle's orientation (attitude) about its center of gravity.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] The control systems include actuators, which exert forces in various directions, and generate rotational forces or moments about the center of gravity of the aircraft, and thus rotate the aircraft in pitch, roll, or yaw.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] For example, a pitching moment is a vertical force applied at a distance forward or aft from the center of gravity of the aircraft, causing the aircraft to pitch up or down.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] Roll, pitch and yaw refer, in this context, to rotations about the respective axes starting from a defined equilibrium state.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] The equilibrium roll angle is known as wings level or zero bank angle, equivalent to a level heeling angle on a ship.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] A fixed-wing aircraft increases or decreases the lift generated by the wings when it pitches nose up or down by increasing or decreasing the angle of attack (AOA).
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] The roll angle is also known as bank angle on a fixed-wing aircraft, which usually "banks" to change the horizontal direction of flight.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] An aircraft is streamlined from nose to tail to reduce drag making it advantageous to keep the sideslip angle near zero, though aircraft are deliberately "side-slipped" when landing in a cross-wind, as explained in slip (aerodynamics).
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] The vehicle's attitude must be controlled during powered atmospheric flight because of its effect on the aerodynamic and propulsive forces.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] There are other reasons, unrelated to flight dynamics, for controlling the vehicle's attitude in non-powered flight (e.g., thermal control, solar power generation, communications, or astronomical observation).
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] The flight dynamics of spacecraft differ from those of aircraft in that the aerodynamic forces are of very small, or vanishingly small effect for most of the vehicle's flight, and cannot be used for attitude control during that time.
[src:uav-flight-control/flight-dynamics] Also, most of a spacecraft's flight time is usually unpowered, leaving gravity as the dominant force.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A **gyroscope** (from Ancient Greek γῦρος *gŷros* 'round' and σκοπέω *skopéō* 'to look') is a device used for measuring or maintaining orientation and angular velocity.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It is a spinning wheel or disc in which the axis of rotation (spin axis) is free to assume any orientation by itself.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] When rotating, the orientation of this axis is unaffected by tilting or rotation of the mounting, due to the conservation of angular momentum.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopes based on other operating principles also exist, such as the microchip-packaged MEMS gyroscopes found in electronic devices (sometimes called **gyrometers**), solid-state ring lasers, fibre optic gyroscopes, and the extremely sensitive quantum gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Applications of gyroscopes include inertial navigation systems, such as in the Hubble Space Telescope, or inside the steel hull of a submerged submarine.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Due to their precision, gyroscopes are also used in gyrotheodolites to maintain direction in tunnel mining.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopes can be used to construct gyrocompasses, which complement or replace magnetic compasses (in ships, aircraft and spacecraft, vehicles in general), to assist in stability (bicycles, motorcycles, and ships; known as **gyrostabilization**) or be used as part of an inertial guidance system.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] MEMS (microelectromechanical system) gyroscopes are popular in some consumer electronics, such as smartphones.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A gyroscope is an instrument, consisting of a wheel mounted into two or three gimbals providing pivoted supports, for allowing the wheel to rotate about a single axis.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A set of three gimbals, one mounted on the other with orthogonal pivot axes, may be used to allow a wheel mounted on the innermost gimbal to have an orientation remaining independent of the orientation, in space, of its support.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In the case of a gyroscope with two gimbals, the outer gimbal, which is the gyroscope frame, is mounted so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane determined by the support.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This outer gimbal possesses one degree of rotational freedom and its axis possesses none.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The second (inner) gimbal is mounted in the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal) so as to pivot about an axis in its own plane that is always perpendicular to the pivotal axis of the gyroscope frame (outer gimbal).
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This inner gimbal has two degrees of rotational freedom.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The axle of the spinning wheel (the rotor) defines the spin axis.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The rotor is constrained to spin about an axis, which is always perpendicular to the axis of the inner gimbal.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] So the rotor possesses three degrees of rotational freedom and its axis possesses two.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The rotor responds to a force applied to the input axis by a reaction force to the output axis.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A gyroscope flywheel will roll or resist about the output axis depending upon whether the output gimbals are of a free or fixed configuration.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] An example of some free-output-gimbal devices is the attitude control gyroscopes used to sense or measure the pitch, roll and yaw attitude angles in a spacecraft or aircraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The centre of gravity of the rotor can be in a fixed position.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The rotor simultaneously spins about one axis and is capable of oscillating about the two other axes, and it is free to turn in any direction about the fixed point (except for its inherent resistance caused by rotor spin).
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Some gyroscopes have mechanical equivalents substituted for one or more of the elements.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] For example, the spinning rotor may be suspended in a fluid, instead of being mounted in gimbals.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A control moment gyroscope (CMG) is an example of a fixed-output-gimbal device that is used on spacecraft to hold or maintain a desired attitude angle or pointing direction using the gyroscopic resistance force.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In some special cases, the outer gimbal (or its equivalent) may be omitted so that the rotor has only two degrees of freedom.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In other cases, the centre of gravity of the rotor may be offset from the axis of oscillation, and thus the centre of gravity of the rotor and the centre of suspension of the rotor may not coincide.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Essentially, a gyroscope is a top combined with a pair of gimbals.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Tops were invented in many different civilizations, including classical Greece, Rome, and China.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Most of these were not utilized as instruments.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The first known apparatus similar to a gyroscope (the "Whirling Speculum" or "Serson's Speculum") was invented by John Serson in 1743.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It was used as a level, to locate the horizon in foggy or misty conditions.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The first instrument used more like an actual gyroscope was made by Johann Bohnenberger of Germany, who first wrote about it in 1817.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Bohnenberger's machine was based on a rotating massive sphere.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Johnson developed a similar device that was based on a rotating disc.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The French mathematician Pierre-Simon Laplace, working at the École Polytechnique in Paris, recommended the machine for use as a teaching aid, and thus it came to the attention of Léon Foucault.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In 1852, Foucault used it in an experiment demonstrating the rotation of the Earth.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It was Foucault who gave the device its modern name, in an experiment to see (Greek *skopeein* 'to see') the Earth's rotation (Greek *gyros* 'circle, rotation'), which was visible in the 8 to 10 minutes before friction slowed the spinning rotor.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In the 1860s, the advent of electric motors made it possible for a gyroscope to spin indefinitely; this led to the first prototype heading indicators, and a rather more complicated device, the gyrocompass.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The first functional gyrocompass was patented in 1904 by German inventor Hermann Anschütz-Kaempfe.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] American Elmer Sperry followed with his own design later that year, and other nations soon realized the military importance of the invention—in an age in which naval prowess was the most significant measure of military power—and created their own gyroscope industries.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The Sperry Gyroscope Company quickly expanded to provide aircraft and naval stabilizers as well, and other gyroscope developers followed suit.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Hurst Mfg Co of Indianapolis started producing the "Hurst gyroscope" a toy gyroscope with a pull string and pedestal.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Manufacture was at some point switched to Chandler Mfg Co (still branded Hurst).
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The product was later renamed to a "Chandler gyroscope", presumably because Chandler Mfg Co. took over rights to the gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Chandler continued to produce the toy until the company was purchased by TEDCO Inc. in 1982.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The gyroscope is still produced by TEDCO today.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Similar principles were later employed in the development of inertial navigation systems for ballistic missiles.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] During World War II, the gyroscope became the prime component for aircraft and anti-aircraft gun sights.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] After the war, the race to miniaturize gyroscopes for guided missiles and weapons navigation systems resulted in the development and manufacturing of so-called **midget gyroscopes** that weighed less than 3 ounces (85 g) and had a diameter of approximately 1 inch (2.5 cm).
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Some of these miniaturized gyroscopes could reach a speed of 24,000 revolutions per minute in less than 10 seconds.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopes continue to be an engineering challenge.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] For example, the axle bearings have to be extremely accurate.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A small amount of friction is deliberately introduced to the bearings, since otherwise an accuracy of better than $10^{-7}$ of an inch (2.5 nm) would be required.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Three-axis MEMS-based gyroscopes are also used in portable electronic devices such as tablets, smartphones, and smartwatches.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This adds to the 3-axis acceleration sensing ability available on previous generations of devices.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Together these sensors provide 6 component motion sensing; accelerometers for X, Y, and Z movement, and gyroscopes for measuring the extent and rate of rotation in space (roll, pitch and yaw).
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Some devices additionally incorporate a magnetometer to provide absolute angular measurements relative to the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Newer MEMS-based inertial measurement units incorporate up to all nine axes of sensing in a single integrated circuit package, providing inexpensive and widely available motion sensing.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] All spinning objects have gyroscopic properties.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The main properties that an object can experience in any gyroscopic motion are rigidity in space and precession.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Rigidity in space describes the principle that a gyroscope remains in the fixed position on the plane in which it is spinning, unaffected by the Earth's rotation. such as with a rotating bike wheel.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Early forms of gyroscope (not then known by the name) were used to demonstrate the principle.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] where $\phi '$ represents precession, $\psi '$ is represented by spin, $\theta$ is the nutation angle, and I represents inertia along its respective axis.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This relation is only valid when the moments along the Y and Z axes are equal to 0.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The equation can be further reduced noting that the angular velocity along the z-axis is equal to the sum of the precession and the spin: $\omega _{z}=\phi '\cos \theta +\psi '$ , Where $\omega _{z}$ represents the angular velocity along the z axis.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopic precession is torque induced.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It is the rate of change of the angular momentum that is produced by the applied torque.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Precession produces counterintuitive dynamic results such as a spinning top not falling over.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Precession is used in aerospace applications for sensing changes of attitude and direction.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A Steadicam rig was employed during the filming of the 1983 film *Return of the Jedi*, in conjunction with two gyroscopes for extra stabilization, to film the background plates for the speeder bike chase.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Steadicam inventor Garrett Brown operated the shot, walking through a redwood forest, running the camera at one frame per second.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] When projected at 24 frames per second, it gave the impression of flying through the air at perilous speeds.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The heading indicator or directional gyro has an axis of rotation that is set horizontally, pointing north.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Unlike a magnetic compass, it does not seek north.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] When being used in an airplane, for example, it will slowly drift away from north and will need to be reoriented periodically, using a magnetic compass as a reference.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Unlike a directional gyro or heading indicator, a gyrocompass seeks north.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It detects the rotation of the Earth about its axis and seeks the *true* north, rather than the *magnetic* north.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyrocompasses usually have built-in damping to prevent overshoot when re-calibrating from sudden movement.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] By determining an object's acceleration and integrating over time, the velocity of the object can be calculated.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Integrating again, position can be determined.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The simplest accelerometer is a weight that is free to move horizontally, which is attached to a spring and a device to measure the tension in the spring.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This can be improved by introducing a counteracting force to push the weight back and to measure the force needed to prevent the weight from moving.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A more complicated design consists of a gyroscope with a weight on one of the axes.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The device will react to the force generated by the weight when it is accelerated, by integrating that force to produce a velocity.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A **gyrostat** consists of a massive flywheel concealed in a solid casing.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Its behaviour on a table, or with various modes of suspension or support, serves to illustrate the curious reversal of the ordinary laws of static equilibrium due to the gyrostatic behaviour of the interior invisible flywheel when rotated rapidly.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The first gyrostat was designed by Lord Kelvin to illustrate the more complicated state of motion of a spinning body when free to wander about on a horizontal plane, like a top spun on the pavement, or a bicycle on the road.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Kelvin also made use of gyrostats to develop mechanical theories of the elasticity of matter and of the ether.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In modern continuum mechanics there is a variety of these models, based on ideas of Lord Kelvin.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] They represent a specific type of Cosserat theories (suggested for the first time by Eugène Cosserat and François Cosserat), which can be used for description of artificially made smart materials as well as of other complex media.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] One of them, so-called Kelvin's medium, has the same equations as magnetic insulators near the state of magnetic saturation in the approximation of quasimagnetostatics.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In modern times, the gyrostat concept is used in the design of attitude control systems for orbiting spacecraft and satellites.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] For instance, the Mir space station had three pairs of internally mounted flywheels known as *gyrodynes* or control moment gyroscopes.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In physics, there are several systems whose dynamical equations resemble the equations of motion of a gyrostat.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscope is a miniaturized gyroscope found in electronic devices.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It takes the idea of the Foucault pendulum and uses a vibrating element.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This kind of gyroscope was first used in military applications but has since been adopted for increasing commercial use.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The hemispherical resonator gyroscope (HRG), also called a wine-glass gyroscope or mushroom gyro, makes use of a thin solid-state hemispherical shell, anchored by a thick stem.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This shell is driven to a flexural resonance by electrostatic forces generated by electrodes which are deposited directly onto separate fused-quartz structures that surround the shell.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopic effect is obtained from the inertial property of the flexural standing waves.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A vibrating structure gyroscope (VSG), also called a Coriolis vibratory gyroscope (CVG), uses a resonator made of different metallic alloys.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It takes a position between the low-accuracy, low-cost MEMS gyroscope and the higher-accuracy and higher-cost fiber optic gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Accuracy parameters are increased by using low-intrinsic damping materials, resonator vacuumization, and digital electronics to reduce temperature dependent drift and instability of control signals.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] High quality wine-glass resonators are used for precise sensors like HRG.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A dynamically tuned gyroscope (DTG) is a rotor suspended by a universal joint with flexure pivots.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The flexure spring stiffness is independent of spin rate.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] However, the dynamic inertia (from the gyroscopic reaction effect) from the gimbal provides negative spring stiffness proportional to the square of the spin speed (Howe and Savet, 1964; Lawrence, 1998).
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Therefore, at a particular speed, called the tuning speed, the two moments cancel each other, freeing the rotor from torque, a necessary condition for an ideal gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A ring laser gyroscope relies on the Sagnac effect to measure rotation by measuring the shifting interference pattern of a beam split into two separate beams which travel around the ring in opposite directions.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] When the Boeing 757-200 entered service in 1983, it was equipped with the first suitable ring laser gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This gyroscope took many years to develop, and the experimental models went through many changes before it was deemed ready for production by the engineers and managers of Honeywell and Boeing.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It was an outcome of the competition with mechanical gyroscopes, which kept improving.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The reason Honeywell, of all companies, chose to develop the laser gyro was that they were the only one that did not have a successful line of mechanical gyroscopes, so they would not be competing against themselves.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The first problem they had to solve was that with laser gyros rotations below a certain minimum could not be detected at all, due to a problem called "lock-in", whereby the two beams act like coupled oscillators and pull each other's frequencies toward convergence and therefore zero output.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The solution was to shake the gyro rapidly so that it never settled into lock-in.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Paradoxically, too regular of a dithering motion produced an accumulation of short periods of lock-in when the device was at rest at the extremities of its shaking motion.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This was cured by applying a random white noise to the vibration.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The material of the block was also changed from quartz to a new glass ceramic Cer-Vit, made by Owens Corning, because of helium leaks.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A fiber optic gyroscope also uses the interference of light to detect mechanical rotation.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The two-halves of the split beam travel in opposite directions in a coil of fiber optic cable as long as 5 km.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Like the ring laser gyroscope, it makes use of the Sagnac effect.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A London moment gyroscope relies on the quantum-mechanical phenomenon, whereby a spinning superconductor generates a magnetic field whose axis lines up exactly with the spin axis of the gyroscopic rotor.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A magnetometer determines the orientation of the generated field, which is interpolated to determine the axis of rotation.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopes of this type can be extremely accurate and stable.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] For example, those used in the Gravity Probe B experiment measured changes in gyroscope spin axis orientation to better than 0.5 milliarcseconds (1.4×10−7 degrees, or about 2.4×10−9 radians) over a one-year period.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] This is equivalent to an angular separation the width of a human hair viewed from 32 kilometers (20 mi) away.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The GP-B gyro consists of a nearly-perfect spherical rotating mass made of fused quartz, which provides a dielectric support for a thin layer of niobium superconducting material.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] To eliminate friction found in conventional bearings, the rotor assembly is centered by the electric field from six electrodes.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] After the initial spin-up by a jet of helium which brings the rotor to 4,000 RPM, the polished gyroscope housing is evacuated to an ultra-high vacuum to further reduce drag on the rotor.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Provided the suspension electronics remain powered, the extreme rotational symmetry, lack of friction, and low drag will allow the angular momentum of the rotor to keep it spinning for about 15,000 years.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A sensitive DC SQUID that can discriminate changes as small as one quantum, or about 2 ×10−15 Wb, is used to monitor the gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A precession, or tilt, in the orientation of the rotor causes the London moment magnetic field to shift relative to the housing.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The moving field passes through a superconducting pickup loop fixed to the housing, inducing a small electric current.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The current produces a voltage across a shunt resistance, which is resolved to spherical coordinates by a microprocessor.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The system is designed to minimize Lorentz torque on the rotor.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The main rotor of a helicopter acts like a gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Its motion is influenced by the principle of gyroscopic precession which is the concept that a force applied to a spinning object will have a maximum reaction approximately 90 degrees later.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The reaction may differ from 90 degrees when other stronger forces are in play.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] To change direction, helicopters must adjust the pitch angle and the angle of attack.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyro X prototype vehicle created by Alex Tremulis and Thomas Summers in 1967.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The car utilized gyroscopic precession to drive on two wheels.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] An assembly consisting of a flywheel mounted in a gimbal housing under the hood of the vehicle acted as a large gyroscope.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The flywheel was rotated by hydraulic pumps creating a gyroscopic effect on the vehicle.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] A precessional ram was responsible for rotating the gyroscope to change the direction of the precessional force to counteract any forces causing the vehicle imbalance.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The one-of-a-kind prototype is now at the Lane Motor Museum in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] In addition to being used in compasses, aircraft, computer pointing devices, etc., gyroscopes have been introduced into consumer electronics.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Since the gyroscope allows the calculation of orientation and rotation, designers have incorporated them into modern technology.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] The integration of the gyroscope has allowed for more accurate recognition of movement within a 3D space than the previous lone accelerometer within a number of smartphones.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Gyroscopes in consumer electronics are frequently combined with accelerometers for more robust direction- and motion-sensing.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Examples of such applications include smartphones such as the Samsung Galaxy Note 4, HTC Titan, Nexus 5, iPhone 5s, Nokia 808 PureView and Sony Xperia, game console peripherals such as the PlayStation 3 controller and the Wii Remote, and virtual reality headsets such as the Oculus Rift.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Some features of Android phones like PhotoSphere or 360 Camera and to use VR gadget do not work without a gyroscope sensor in the phone.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Nintendo has integrated a gyroscope into the Wii console's Wii Remote controller by an additional piece of hardware called "Wii MotionPlus".
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] It is also included in the 3DS, Wii U GamePad, and Nintendo Switch Joy-Con and Pro controllers, which detect movement when turning and shaking.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] Cruise ships use gyroscopes to level motion-sensitive devices such as self-leveling pool tables.
[src:uav-flight-control/gyroscope] An electric powered flywheel gyroscope inserted in a bicycle wheel is sold as an alternative to training wheels.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] An **inertial measurement unit** (**IMU**) is an electronic device that measures and reports a body's specific force, angular rate, and sometimes the orientation of the body, using a combination of accelerometers, gyroscopes, and sometimes magnetometers.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] When the magnetometer is included, IMUs are referred to as IMMUs.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are typically used to maneuver modern vehicles including motorcycles, missiles, aircraft (an attitude and heading reference system), including uncrewed aerial vehicles (UAVs), among many others, and spacecraft, including satellites and landers.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Recent developments allow for the production of IMU-enabled GPS devices; an IMU allows a GPS receiver to work when GPS-signals are unavailable, such as in tunnels, inside buildings, or when electronic interference is present.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are used in VR headsets and smartphones, and also in motion tracked game controllers like the Wii Remote, Steam Controller, Nintendo Switch Pro Controller and the Dualsense.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] An inertial measurement unit works by detecting linear acceleration using one or more accelerometers and rotational rate using one or more gyroscopes.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Some also include a magnetometer which is commonly used as a heading reference.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Some IMUs, like the BNO055 used within Adafruit's 9-DOF IMU Breakout, include additional sensors like temperature.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Typical configurations contain one accelerometer, gyro, and magnetometer per axis for each of the three principal axes: pitch, roll and yaw.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are often incorporated into Inertial Navigation Systems, which utilize the raw IMU measurements to calculate attitude, angular rates, linear velocity, and position relative to a global reference frame.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] The IMU equipped INS forms the backbone for the navigation and control of many commercial and military vehicles, such as crewed aircraft, missiles, ships, submarines, and satellites.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are also essential components in the guidance and control of uncrewed systems such as UAVs, UGVs, and UUVs.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Simpler versions of INSs termed Attitude and Heading Reference Systems utilize IMUs to calculate vehicle attitude with heading relative to magnetic north.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] The data collected from the IMU's sensors allows a computer to track craft's position, using a method known as dead reckoning.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] This data is usually presented in Euler vectors representing the angles of rotation in the three primary axis or a quaternion.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Besides navigational purposes, IMUs serve as orientation sensors in many consumer products.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Almost all smartphones and tablets contain IMUs as orientation sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Fitness trackers and other wearables may also include IMUs to measure motion, such as running.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs also have the ability to determine developmental levels of individuals when in motion by identifying specificity and sensitivity of specific parameters associated with running.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Some gaming systems such as the remote controls for the Nintendo Wii use IMUs to measure motion.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Low-cost IMUs have enabled the proliferation of the consumer drone industry.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] They are also frequently used for sports technology (technique training), and animation applications.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] They are a competing technology for use in motion capture technology.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] An IMU is at the heart of the balancing technology used in the Segway Personal Transporter.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] In a navigation system, the data reported by the IMU is fed into a processor which calculates altitude, velocity and position.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] A typical implementation referred to as a Strap Down Inertial System integrates angular rate from the gyroscope to calculate angular position.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] This is fused with the gravity vector measured by the accelerometers in a Kalman filter to estimate attitude.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] The attitude estimate is used to transform acceleration measurements into an inertial reference frame (hence the term inertial navigation) where they are integrated once to get linear velocity, and twice to get linear position.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] This method of navigation is called dead reckoning.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] One of the earliest units was designed and built by Ford Instrument Company for the USAF to help aircraft navigate in flight without any input from outside the aircraft.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Called the **Ground-Position Indicator**, once the pilot entered in the aircraft longitude and latitude at takeoff, the unit would show the pilot the longitude and latitude of the aircraft in relation to the ground.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Positional tracking systems like GPS can be used to continually correct drift errors (an application of the Kalman filter).
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] A major disadvantage of using IMUs for navigation is that they typically suffer from accumulated error.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Because the guidance system is continually integrating acceleration with respect to time to calculate velocity and position *(see dead reckoning)*, any measurement errors, however small, are accumulated over time.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] This leads to 'drift': an ever-increasing difference between where the system thinks it is located and the actual location.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Due to integration a constant error in acceleration results in a linear error growth in velocity and a quadratic error growth in position.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] A constant error in attitude rate (gyro) results in a quadratic error growth in velocity and a cubic error growth in position.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] To get a rough idea, this means that, for a single, uncorrected accelerometer, the cheapest (at 100 mg) loses its ability to give 50-meter accuracy after around 10 seconds, while the best accelerometer (at 10 μg) loses its 50-meter accuracy after around 17 minutes.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] The accuracy of the inertial sensors inside a modern inertial measurement unit (IMU) has a more complex impact on the performance of an inertial navigation system (INS).
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] All these errors depend on various physical phenomena specific to each sensor technology.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Depending on the targeted applications and to be able to make the proper sensor choice, it is very important to consider the needs regarding stability, repeatability, and environment sensitivity (mainly thermal and mechanical environments), on both short and long terms.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Targeted performance for applications is, most of the time, better than a sensor's absolute performance.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] However, sensor performance is repeatable over time, with more or less accuracy, and therefore can be assessed and compensated to enhance its performance.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] This real-time performance enhancement is based on both sensors and IMU models.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Complexity for these models will then be chosen according to the needed performance and the type of application considered.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Ability to define this model is part of sensors and IMU manufacturers know-how.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Sensors and IMU models are computed in factories through a dedicated calibration sequence using multi-axis turntables and climatic chambers.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] They can either be computed for each individual product or generic for the whole production.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Calibration will typically improve a sensor's raw performance by at least two decades.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] High performance IMUs, or IMUs designed to operate under harsh conditions, are very often suspended by shock absorbers.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Suspended IMUs can offer very high performance, even when submitted to harsh environments.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] Decreasing these errors tends to push IMU designers to increase processing frequencies, which becomes easier using recent digital technologies.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] However, developing algorithms able to cancel these errors requires deep inertial knowledge and strong intimacy with sensors/IMU design.
[src:uav-flight-control/inertial-measurement-unit] On the other hand, if suspension is likely to enable IMU performance increase, it has a side effect on size and mass.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A **proportional–integral–derivative** (**PID**) **controller**, or **three-term controller**, is a feedback-based control loop mechanism commonly used to manage machines and processes that require continuous control and automatic adjustment.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It is typically used in industrial control systems and various other applications where constant control through modulation is necessary without human intervention.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller automatically compares the desired target value (setpoint or SP) with the actual value of the system (process variable or PV).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The difference between these two values is called the *error value*, denoted as $e(t)$ .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It then applies corrective actions automatically to bring the PV to the same value as the SP using three methods: The proportional (*P*) component responds to the current error value by producing an output that is directly proportional to the magnitude of the error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This provides immediate correction based on how far the system is from the desired setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The integral (*I*) component, in turn, considers the cumulative sum of past errors to address any residual steady-state errors that persist over time, eliminating lingering discrepancies.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Lastly, the derivative (*D*) component predicts future error by assessing the rate of change of the error, which helps to mitigate overshoot and enhance system stability, particularly when the system undergoes rapid changes.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID output signal can directly control actuators through voltage, current, or other modulation methods, depending on the application.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller reduces the likelihood of human error and improves automation.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A common example is a vehicle’s cruise control system.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] For instance, when a vehicle encounters a hill, its speed will decrease if the engine power output is kept constant.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller adjusts the engine's power output to restore the vehicle to its desired speed, doing so efficiently with minimal delay and overshoot.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The theoretical foundation of PID controllers dates back to the early 1920s with the development of automatic steering systems for ships.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This concept was later adopted for automatic process control in manufacturing, first appearing in pneumatic actuators and evolving into electronic controllers.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers are widely used in numerous applications requiring accurate, stable, and optimized automatic control, such as temperature regulation, motor speed control, and industrial process management.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The most distinguishing feature of the PID controller is the ability to use the three *control terms* of proportional, integral and derivative influence on the controller output to apply accurate and optimal control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The block diagram on the right shows the principles of how these terms are generated and applied.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It shows a PID controller, which continuously calculates an *error value* $e(t)$ as the difference between a desired setpoint ${\text{SP}}=r(t)$ and a measured process variable ${\text{PV}}=y(t)$ : $e(t)=r(t)-y(t)$ , and applies a correction based on proportional, integral, and derivative terms.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The controller attempts to minimize the error over time by adjustment of a *control variable* $u(t)$ , such as the opening of a control valve, to a new value determined by a weighted sum of the control terms.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller directly generates a continuous control signal based on error, without discrete modulation.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] where $K_{\text{p}}$ , $K_{\text{i}}$ , and $K_{\text{d}}$ , all non-negative, denote the coefficients for the proportional, integral, and derivative terms respectively (sometimes denoted *P*, *I*, and *D*).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Although a PID controller has three control terms, some applications need only one or two terms to provide appropriate control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This is achieved by setting the unused parameters to zero and is called a PI, PD, P, or I controller in the absence of the other control actions.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] PI controllers are fairly common in applications where derivative action would be sensitive to measurement noise, but the integral term is often needed for the system to reach its target value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The use of the PID algorithm does not guarantee optimal control of the system or its control stability .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Situations may occur where there are excessive delays: the measurement of the process value is delayed, or the control action does not apply quickly enough.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In these cases, lead–lag compensation is required to be effective.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The response of the controller can be described in terms of its responsiveness to an error, the degree to which the system overshoots a setpoint, and the degree of any system oscillation.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] But the PID controller is broadly applicable since it relies only on the response of the measured process variable, not on knowledge or a model of the underlying process.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The centrifugal governor was invented by Christiaan Huygens in the 17th century to regulate the gap between millstones in windmills depending on the speed of rotation, and thereby compensate for the variable speed of grain feed.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] With the invention of the low-pressure stationary steam engine, there was a need for automatic speed control, and James Watt's self-designed "conical pendulum" governor, a set of revolving steel balls attached to a vertical spindle by link arms, came to be an industry standard.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This was based on the millstone-gap control concept.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Rotating-governor speed control, however, was still variable under conditions of varying load, where the shortcoming of what is now known as proportional control alone was evident.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The error between the desired speed and the actual speed would increase with increasing load.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In the 19th century, the theoretical basis for the operation of governors was first described by James Clerk Maxwell in 1868 in his now-famous paper *On Governors*.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] He explored the mathematical basis for control stability and progressed a good way towards a solution, but made an appeal for mathematicians to examine the problem.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The problem was examined further in 1874 by Edward Routh, Charles Sturm, and in 1895, Adolf Hurwitz, all of whom contributed to the establishment of control stability criteria.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In subsequent applications, speed governors were further refined, notably by American scientist Willard Gibbs, who in 1872 theoretically analyzed Watt's conical pendulum governor.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] About this time, the invention of the Whitehead torpedo posed a control problem that required accurate control of the running depth.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Use of a depth pressure sensor alone proved inadequate, and a pendulum that measured the fore and aft pitch of the torpedo was combined with depth measurement to become the pendulum-and-hydrostat control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Pressure control provided only a proportional control that, if the control gain was too high, would become unstable and go into overshoot with considerable instability of depth-holding.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The pendulum added what is now known as derivative control, which damped the oscillations by detecting the torpedo dive/climb angle and thereby the rate-of-change of depth.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This development (named by Whitehead as "The Secret" to give no clue to its action) was around 1868.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Another early example of a PID-type controller was developed by Elmer Sperry in 1911 for ship steering, though his work was intuitive rather than mathematically-based.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It was not until 1922, however, that a formal control law for what we now call PID or three-term control was first developed using theoretical analysis, by Russian American engineer Nicolas Minorsky.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Minorsky was researching and designing automatic ship steering for the US Navy and based his analysis on observations of a helmsman.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] He noted the helmsman steered the ship based not only on the current course error but also on past error, as well as the current rate of change; this was then given a mathematical treatment by Minorsky.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] His goal was stability, not general control, which simplified the problem significantly.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] While proportional control provided stability against small disturbances, it was insufficient for dealing with a steady disturbance, notably a stiff gale (due to steady-state error), which required adding the integral term.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Finally, the derivative term was added to improve stability and control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Trials were carried out on the USS *New Mexico*, with the controllers controlling the *angular velocity* (not the angle) of the rudder.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] PI control yielded sustained yaw (angular error) of ±2°.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Adding the D element yielded a yaw error of ±1/6°, better than most helmsmen could achieve.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The Navy ultimately did not adopt the system due to resistance by personnel.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Similar work was carried out and published by several others in the 1930s.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The wide use of feedback controllers did not become feasible until the development of wideband high-gain amplifiers to use the concept of negative feedback.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This had been developed in telephone engineering electronics by Harold Black in the late 1920s, but not published until 1934.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Independently, Clesson E Mason of the Foxboro Company in 1930 invented a wide-band pneumatic controller by combining the nozzle and flapper high-gain pneumatic amplifier, which had been invented in 1914, with negative feedback from the controller output.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This dramatically increased the linear range of operation of the nozzle and flapper amplifier, and integral control could also be added by the use of a precision bleed valve and a bellows generating the integral term.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The result was the "Stabilog" controller, which gave both proportional and integral functions using feedback bellows.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Later, the derivative term was added by a further bellows and adjustable orifice.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] From about 1932 onwards, the use of wideband pneumatic controllers increased rapidly in a variety of control applications.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Air pressure was used for generating the controller output, and also for powering process modulating devices such as diaphragm-operated control valves.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] They were simple low maintenance devices that operated well in harsh industrial environments and did not present explosion risks in hazardous locations.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] They were the industry standard for many decades until the advent of discrete electronic controllers and distributed control systems (DCSs).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] With these controllers, a pneumatic industry signaling standard of 3–15 psi (0.2–1.0 bar) was established, which had an elevated zero to ensure devices were working within their linear characteristic and represented the control range of 0-100%.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In the 1950s, when high-gain electronic amplifiers became cheap and reliable, electronic PID controllers became popular, and the pneumatic standard was emulated by 10-50 mA and 4–20 mA current loop signals (the latter became the industry standard).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Pneumatic field actuators are still widely used because of the advantages of pneumatic energy for control valves in process plant environments.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Most modern PID controls in industry are implemented as computer software in DCSs, programmable logic controllers (PLCs), or discrete compact controllers.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Electronic analog PID control loops were often found within more complex electronic systems, for example, the head positioning of a disk drive, the power conditioning of a power supply, or even the movement-detection circuit of a modern seismometer.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Discrete electronic analog controllers have been largely replaced by digital controllers using microcontrollers or FPGAs to implement PID algorithms.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] However, discrete analog PID controllers are still used in niche applications requiring high-bandwidth and low-noise performance, such as laser-diode controllers.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Consider a robotic arm that can be moved and positioned by a control loop.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] An electric motor may lift or lower the arm, depending on forward or reverse power applied, but power cannot be a simple function of position because of the inertial mass of the arm, forces due to gravity, external forces on the arm such as a load to lift or work to be done on an external object.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID controller continuously adjusts the input current to achieve smooth motion.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] By measuring the position (PV) and subtracting it from the setpoint (SP), the error (e) is found, and from it, the controller calculates how much electric current (MV) to supply to the motor.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The obvious method is **proportional** control: the motor current is set in proportion to the existing error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] However, this method fails if, for instance, the arm has to lift different weights: a greater weight needs a greater force applied for the same error on the down side, but a smaller force if the error is low on the upside.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] That's where the integral and derivative terms play their part.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] An **integral** term increases action in relation not only to the error but also the time for which it has persisted.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] So, if the applied force is not enough to bring the error to zero, this force will be increased as time passes.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Applying too much integral when the error is small and decreasing will lead to overshoot.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] After overshooting, if the controller were to apply a large correction in the opposite direction and repeatedly overshoot the desired position, the output would oscillate around the setpoint in either a constant, growing, or decaying sinusoid.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the amplitude of the oscillations increases with time, the system is unstable.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the oscillations remain at a constant magnitude, the system is marginally stable.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A **derivative** term does not consider the magnitude of the error (meaning it cannot bring it to zero: a pure D controller cannot bring the system to its setpoint), but rather the rate of change of error, trying to bring this rate to zero.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It aims at flattening the error trajectory into a horizontal line, damping the force applied, and so reduces overshoot (error on the other side because of too great applied force).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In the interest of achieving a controlled arrival at the desired position (SP) in a timely and accurate way, the controlled system needs to be critically damped.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A well-tuned position control system will also apply the necessary currents to the controlled motor so that the arm pushes and pulls as necessary to resist external forces trying to move it away from the required position.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The setpoint itself may be generated by an external system, such as a PLC or other computer system, so that it continuously varies depending on the work that the robotic arm is expected to do.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A well-tuned PID control system will enable the arm to meet these changing requirements to the best of its capabilities.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If a controller starts from a stable state with zero error (PV = SP), then further changes by the controller will be in response to changes in other measured or unmeasured inputs to the process that affect the process, and hence the PV.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Variables that affect the process other than the MV are known as disturbances.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Generally, controllers are used to reject disturbances and to implement setpoint changes.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A change in load on the arm constitutes a disturbance to the robot arm control process.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In theory, a controller can be used to control any process that has a measurable output (PV), a known ideal value for that output (SP), and an input to the process (MV) that will affect the relevant PV.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Controllers are used in industry to regulate temperature, pressure, force, feed rate, flow rate, chemical composition (component concentrations), weight, position, speed, and practically every other variable for which a measurement exists.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This section describes the parallel or non-interacting form of the PID controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The PID control scheme is named after its three correcting terms, whose sum constitutes the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The proportional, integral, and derivative terms are summed to calculate the output of the PID controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] where s is the complex angular frequency.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The proportional term produces an output value that is proportional to the current error value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The proportional response can be adjusted by multiplying the error by a constant *K*p, called the proportional gain constant.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A high proportional gain results in a large change in the output for a given change in the error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the proportional gain is too high, the system can become unstable (see the section on loop tuning).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In contrast, a small gain results in a small output response to a large input error, and a less responsive or less sensitive controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the proportional gain is too low, the control action may be too small when responding to system disturbances.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Tuning theory and industrial practice indicate that the proportional term should contribute the bulk of the output change.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The **steady-state error** is the difference between the desired final output and the actual one.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Because a non-zero error is required to drive it, a proportional controller generally operates with a steady-state error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Steady-state error (SSE) is proportional to the process gain and inversely proportional to proportional gain.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] SSE may be mitigated by adding a compensating bias term to the setpoint AND output or corrected dynamically by adding an integral term.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The contribution from the integral term is proportional to both the magnitude of the error and the duration of the error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The integral in a PID controller is the sum of the instantaneous error over time and gives the accumulated offset that should have been corrected previously.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The accumulated error is then multiplied by the integral gain (*K*i) and added to the controller output.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The integral term accelerates the movement of the process towards setpoint and eliminates the residual steady-state error that occurs with a pure proportional controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] However, since the integral term responds to accumulated errors from the past, it can cause the present value to overshoot the setpoint value (see the section on loop tuning).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The derivative of the process error is calculated by determining the slope of the error over time and multiplying this rate of change by the derivative gain *K*d.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The magnitude of the contribution of the derivative term to the overall control action is termed the derivative gain, *K*d.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Derivative action predicts system behavior and thus improves settling time and stability of the system.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] An ideal derivative is not causal, so that implementations of PID controllers include an additional low-pass filtering for the derivative term to limit the high-frequency gain and noise.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Derivative action is seldom used in practice, though – by one estimate in only 25% of deployed controllers – because of its variable impact on system stability in real-world applications.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Even though there are only three parameters and it is simple to describe in principle, PID tuning is a difficult problem because it must satisfy complex criteria within the limitations of PID control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Accordingly, there are various methods for loop tuning, and more sophisticated techniques are the subject of patents; this section describes some traditional, manual methods for loop tuning.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Designing and tuning a PID controller appears to be conceptually intuitive, but can be hard in practice, if multiple (and often conflicting) objectives, such as short transient and high stability, are to be achieved.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers often provide acceptable control using default tunings, but performance can generally be improved by careful tuning, and performance may be unacceptable with poor tuning.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Usually, initial designs need to be adjusted repeatedly through computer simulations until the closed-loop system performs or compromises as desired.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Some processes have a degree of nonlinearity, so parameters that work well at full-load conditions do not work when the process is starting up from no load.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This can be corrected by gain scheduling (using different parameters in different operating regions).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the PID controller parameters (the gains of the proportional, integral and derivative terms) are chosen incorrectly, the controlled process input can be unstable; i.e., its output diverges, with or without oscillation, and is limited only by saturation or mechanical breakage.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Instability is caused by *excess* gain, particularly in the presence of significant lag.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Generally, stabilization of response is required and the process must not oscillate for any combination of process conditions and setpoints, though sometimes marginal stability (bounded oscillation) is acceptable or desired.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Mathematically, the origins of instability can be seen in the Laplace domain.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] where $K(s)$ is the PID transfer function, and $G(s)$ is the plant transfer function.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A system is *unstable* where the closed-loop transfer function diverges for some s .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This happens in situations where $K(s)G(s)=-1$ .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In other words, this happens when $|K(s)G(s)|=1$ with a 180° phase shift.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Stability is guaranteed when $K(s)G(s)<1$ for frequencies that suffer high phase shifts.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A more general formalism of this effect is known as the Nyquist stability criterion.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The optimal behavior on a process change or setpoint change varies depending on the application.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Two basic requirements are *regulation* (disturbance rejection – staying at a given setpoint) and *command tracking* (implementing setpoint changes).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] These terms refer to how well the controlled variable tracks the desired value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Specific criteria for command tracking include rise time and settling time.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Some processes must not allow an overshoot of the process variable beyond the setpoint if, for example, this would be unsafe.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Other processes must minimize the energy expended in reaching a new setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] There are several methods for tuning a PID loop.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The most effective methods generally involve developing some form of process model and then choosing P, I, and D based on the dynamic model parameters.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Manual tuning methods can be relatively time-consuming, particularly for systems with long loop times.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The choice of method depends largely on whether the loop can be taken offline for tuning, and on the response time of the system.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the system can be taken offline, the best tuning method often involves subjecting the system to a step change in input, measuring the output as a function of time, and using this response to determine the control parameters.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] If the system must remain online, one tuning method is to first set $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ values to zero.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Increase the $K_{p}$ until the output of the loop oscillates; then set $K_{p}$ to approximately half that value for a "quarter amplitude decay"-type response.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Then increase $K_{i}$ until any offset is corrected in sufficient time for the process, but not until too great a value causes instability.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Finally, increase $K_{d}$ , if required, until the loop is acceptably quick to reach its reference after a load disturbance.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Too much $K_{p}$ causes excessive response and overshoot.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Another heuristic tuning method is known as the Ziegler–Nichols method, introduced by John G.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] As in the method above, the $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ gains are first set to zero.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The oscillation frequency is often measured instead, and the reciprocals of each multiplication yields the same result.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] These gains apply to the ideal, parallel form of the PID controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] When applied to the standard PID form, only the integral and derivative gains $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ are dependent on the oscillation period $T_{u}$ .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This method was developed in 1953 and is based on a first-order + time delay model.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Similar to the Ziegler–Nichols method, a set of tuning parameters were developed to yield a closed-loop response with a decay ratio of ${\tfrac {1}{4}}$ .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Arguably, the biggest problem with these parameters is that a small change in the process parameters could potentially cause a closed-loop system to become unstable.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Published in 1984 by Karl Johan Åström and Tore Hägglund, the relay method temporarily operates the process using bang-bang control and measures the resultant oscillations.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The output is switched (as if by a relay, hence the name) between two values of the control variable.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The values must be chosen so the process will cross the setpoint, but they need not be 0% and 100%; by choosing suitable values, dangerous oscillations can be avoided.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] As long as the process variable is below the setpoint, the control output is set to the higher value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] As soon as it rises above the setpoint, the control output is set to the lower value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Ideally, the output waveform is nearly square, spending equal time above and below the setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The period and amplitude of the resultant oscillations are measured and used to compute the ultimate gain and period, which are then fed into the Ziegler–Nichols method.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Specifically, the ultimate period $T_{u}$ is assumed to be equal to the observed period, and the ultimate gain is computed as $K_{u}=4b/\pi a,$ where a is the amplitude of the process variable oscillation, and b is the amplitude of the control output change which caused it.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] There are numerous variants on the relay method.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] where *k*p is the process gain, *τ*p is the time constant, *θ* is the dead time, and *u*(*s*) is a step change input.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It is important when using this method to apply a large enough step-change input that the output can be measured; however, too large of a step change can affect the process stability.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Additionally, a larger step change ensures that the output does not change due to a disturbance (for best results, try to minimize disturbances when performing the step test).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] One way to determine the parameters for the first-order process is to use the 63.2% method.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In this method, the process gain (*k*p) is equal to the change in output divided by the change in input.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The dead time *θ* is the amount of time between when the step change occurred and when the output first changed.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The time constant (*τ*p) is the amount of time it takes for the output to reach 63.2% of the new steady-state value after the step change.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] One downside to using this method is that it can take a while to reach a new steady-state value if the process has large time constants.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Most modern industrial facilities no longer tune loops using the manual calculation methods shown above.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Instead, PID tuning and loop optimization software are used to ensure consistent results.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] These software packages gather data, develop process models, and suggest optimal tuning.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Some software packages can even develop tuning by gathering data from reference changes.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Mathematical PID loop tuning induces an impulse in the system and then uses the controlled system's frequency response to design the PID loop values.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In loops with response times of several minutes, mathematical loop tuning is recommended, because trial and error can take days just to find a stable set of loop values.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Some digital loop controllers offer a self-tuning feature in which very small setpoint changes are sent to the process, allowing the controller itself to calculate optimal tuning values.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Another approach calculates initial values via the Ziegler–Nichols method, and uses a numerical optimization technique to find better PID coefficients.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Other formulas are available to tune the loop according to different performance criteria.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Many patented formulas are now embedded within PID tuning software and hardware modules.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Advances in automated PID loop tuning software also deliver algorithms for tuning PID Loops in a dynamic or non-steady state (NSS) scenario.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The software models the dynamics of a process through a disturbance, and calculate PID control parameters in response.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] While PID controllers are applicable to many control problems and often perform satisfactorily without any improvements or only coarse tuning, they can perform poorly in some applications and do not, in general, provide *optimal* control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The fundamental difficulty with PID control is that it is a feedback control system with *constant* parameters and no direct knowledge of the process, and thus, overall performance is reactive and a compromise.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] While PID control is the best controller for an observer that has no model of the process, better performance can be obtained by overtly modeling the actor of the process without resorting to an observer.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers, when used alone, can give poor performance when the PID loop gains must be reduced so that the control system does not overshoot, oscillate or hunt about the control setpoint value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] They also have difficulties in the presence of non-linearities, may trade-off regulation versus response time, do not react to changing process behavior (say, the process changes after it has warmed up), and have lag in responding to large disturbances.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The most significant improvement is to incorporate feed-forward control with knowledge about the system, and using the PID only to control error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] PID controllers work best when the loop to be controlled is linear and symmetric.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Thus, their performance in non-linear and asymmetric systems is degraded.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A nonlinear valve in a flow control application, for instance, will result in variable loop sensitivity that requires damping to prevent instability.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] One solution is to include a model of the valve's nonlinearity in the control algorithm to compensate for this.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] An asymmetric application, for example, is temperature control in HVAC systems that use only active heating (via a heating element), whereas only passive cooling is available.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Overshoot of rising temperature can only be corrected slowly; active cooling is not available to force temperature downward as a function of the control output.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In this case, the PID controller could be tuned to be over-damped, to prevent or reduce overshoot, but this reduces performance by increasing the settling time of a rising temperature to the set point.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] The inherent degradation of control quality in this application could be solved by application of active cooling.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A problem with the derivative term is that it amplifies higher frequency measurement or process noise that can cause large amounts of change in the output.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] It is often helpful to filter the measurements with a low-pass filter in order to remove higher-frequency noise components.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] As low-pass filtering and derivative control can cancel each other out, the amount of filtering is limited.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] Therefore, low-noise instrumentation can be important.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] A nonlinear median filter may be used, which improves the filtering efficiency and practical performance.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] In some cases, the differential band can be turned off with little loss of control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p01] This is equivalent to using the PID controller as a PI controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The basic PID algorithm presents some challenges in control applications that have been addressed by minor modifications to the PID form.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] One common problem resulting from the ideal PID implementations is integral windup.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Following a large change in setpoint, the integral term can accumulate an error larger than the maximal value for the regulation variable (windup), thus the system overshoots and continues to increase until this accumulated error is unwound.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] For example, a PID loop is used to control the temperature of an electric resistance furnace where the system has stabilized.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Now, when the door is opened and something cold is put into the furnace, the temperature drops below the setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The integral function of the controller tends to compensate for error by introducing another error in the positive direction.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This overshoot can be avoided by freezing of the integral function after the opening of the door for the time the control loop typically needs to reheat the furnace.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] A **PI controller** (proportional–integral controller) is a special case of the PID controller in which the derivative (D) of the error is not used.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] where $\Delta$ is the error or deviation of actual measured value (***PV***) from the setpoint (***SP***).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Setting a value for G is often a trade off between decreasing overshoot and increasing settling time.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The lack of derivative action may make the system more steady in the steady state in the case of noisy data.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This is because derivative action is more sensitive to higher-frequency terms in the inputs.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Without derivative action, a PI-controlled system is less responsive to real (non-noise) and relatively fast alterations in state, and so the system will be slower to reach setpoint and slower to respond to perturbations than a well-tuned PID system may be.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Many PID loops control a mechanical device (for example, a valve).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Mechanical maintenance can be a major cost and wear leads to control degradation in the form of either stiction or backlash in the mechanical response to an input signal.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The rate of mechanical wear is mainly a function of how often a device is activated to make a change.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Where wear is a significant concern, the PID loop may have an output deadband to reduce the frequency of activation of the output (valve).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This is accomplished by modifying the controller to hold its output steady if the change would be small (within the defined deadband range).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The calculated output must leave the deadband before the actual output will change.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The proportional and derivative terms can produce excessive movement in the output when a system is subjected to an instantaneous step increase in the error, such as a large setpoint change.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In the case of the derivative term, this is due to taking the derivative of the error, which is very large in the case of an instantaneous step change.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In this modification, the setpoint is gradually moved from its old value to a newly specified value using a linear or first-order differential ramp function.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In this case, the PID controller measures the derivative of the measured PV, rather than the derivative of the error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This quantity is always continuous (i.e., never has a step change as a result of changed setpoint).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This modification is a simple case of setpoint weighting.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Setpoint weighting adds adjustable factors (usually between 0 and 1) to the setpoint in the error in the proportional and derivative element of the controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The error in the integral term must be the true control error to avoid steady-state control errors.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] These two extra parameters do not affect the response to load disturbances and measurement noise and can be tuned to improve the controller's setpoint response.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The control system performance can be improved by combining the feedback (or closed-loop) control of a PID controller with feed-forward (or open-loop) control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Knowledge about the system (such as the desired acceleration and inertia) can be fed forward and combined with the PID output to improve the overall system performance.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The feed-forward value alone can often provide the major portion of the controller output.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The PID controller primarily has to compensate for whatever difference or *error* remains between the setpoint (SP) and the system response to the open-loop control.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Since the feed-forward output is not affected by the process feedback, it can never cause the control system to oscillate, thus improving the system response without affecting stability.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Feed forward can be based on the setpoint and on extra measured disturbances.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Setpoint weighting is a simple form of feed forward.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] For example, in most motion control systems, in order to accelerate a mechanical load under control, more force is required from the actuator.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] If a velocity loop PID controller is being used to control the speed of the load and command the force being applied by the actuator, then it is beneficial to take the desired instantaneous acceleration, scale that value appropriately and add it to the output of the PID velocity loop controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This means that whenever the load is being accelerated or decelerated, a proportional amount of force is commanded from the actuator regardless of the feedback value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The PID loop in this situation uses the feedback information to change the combined output to reduce the remaining difference between the process setpoint and the feedback value.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Working together, the combined open-loop feed-forward controller and closed-loop PID controller can provide a more responsive control system.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] PID controllers are often implemented with a "bumpless" initialization feature that recalculates the integral accumulator term to maintain a consistent process output through parameter changes.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] A partial implementation is to store the integral gain times the error rather than storing the error and postmultiplying by the integral gain, which prevents discontinuous output when the I gain is changed, but not the P or D gains.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In addition to feed-forward, PID controllers are often enhanced through methods such as PID gain scheduling (changing parameters in different operating conditions), fuzzy logic, or computational verb logic.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Further practical application issues can arise from instrumentation connected to the controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] A high enough sampling rate, measurement precision, and measurement accuracy are required to achieve adequate control performance.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Another new method for improvement of PID controller is to increase the degree of freedom by using fractional order.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The order of the integrator and differentiator add increased flexibility to the controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] One distinctive advantage of PID controllers is that two PID controllers can be used together to yield better dynamic performance.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Two controllers are in cascade when they are arranged so that one regulates the set point of the other.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] A PID controller acts as outer loop controller, which controls the primary physical parameter, such as fluid level or velocity.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The other controller acts as inner loop controller, which reads the output of outer loop controller as setpoint, usually controlling a more rapid changing parameter, flowrate or acceleration.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] It can be mathematically proven that the working frequency of the controller is increased and the time constant of the object is reduced by using cascaded PID controllers..
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] For example, a temperature-controlled circulating bath has two PID controllers in cascade, each with its own thermocouple temperature sensor.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The outer controller controls the temperature of the water using a thermocouple located far from the heater, where it accurately reads the temperature of the bulk of the water.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The error term of this PID controller is the difference between the desired bath temperature and measured temperature.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Instead of controlling the heater directly, the outer PID controller sets a heater temperature goal for the inner PID controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The inner PID controller controls the temperature of the heater using a thermocouple attached to the heater.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The inner controller's error term is the difference between this heater temperature setpoint and the measured temperature of the heater.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Its output controls the actual heater to stay near this setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The proportional, integral, and differential terms of the two controllers will be very different.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The outer PID controller has a long time constant – all the water in the tank needs to heat up or cool down.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The inner loop responds much more quickly.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Each controller can be tuned to match the physics of the system *it* controls – heat transfer and thermal mass of the whole tank or of just the heater – giving better total response.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The form of the PID controller most often encountered in industry, and the one most relevant to tuning algorithms, is the *standard form*.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In this standard form, the parameters have a clear physical meaning.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In particular, the inner summation produces a new single error value, which is compensated for future and past errors.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The proportional error term is the current error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The derivative components term attempts to predict the error value at $T_{d}$ seconds (or samples) in the future, assuming that the loop control remains unchanged.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The integral component adjusts the error value to compensate for the sum of all past errors, with the intention of completely eliminating them in $T_{i}$ seconds (or samples).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The resulting compensated single error value is then scaled by the single gain $K_{p}$ to compute the control variable.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] the gain parameters are related to the parameters of the standard form through $K_{i}=K_{p}/T_{i}$ and $K_{d}=K_{p}T_{d}$ .
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This parallel form, where the parameters are treated as simple gains, is the most general and flexible form.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] However, it is also the form where the parameters have the weakest relationship to physical behaviors and is generally reserved for theoretical treatment of the PID controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The standard form, despite being slightly more complex mathematically, is more common in industry.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In many cases, the manipulated variable output by the PID controller is a dimensionless fraction between 0 and 100% of some maximum possible value, and the translation into real units (such as pumping rate or watts of heater power) is outside the PID controller.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The process variable, however, is in dimensioned units such as temperature.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] It is common in this case to express the gain $K_{p}$ not as "output per degree", but rather in the reciprocal form of a *proportional band* $100/K_{p}$ , which is "degrees per full output": the range over which the output changes from 0 to 1 (0% to 100%).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Beyond this range, the output is saturated, full-off or full-on.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The narrower this band, the higher the proportional gain.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In most commercial control systems, derivative action is based on process variable rather than error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] That is, a change in the setpoint does not affect the derivative action.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This is because the digitized version of the algorithm produces a large unwanted spike when the setpoint is changed.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] If the setpoint is constant, then changes in the PV will be the same as changes in error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Therefore, this modification makes no difference to the way the controller responds to process disturbances.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Most commercial control systems offer the *option* of also basing the proportional action solely on the process variable.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This means that only the integral action responds to changes in the setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The modification to the algorithm does not affect the way the controller responds to process disturbances.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Basing proportional action on PV eliminates the instant and possibly very large change in output caused by a sudden change to the setpoint.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Depending on the process and tuning, this may be beneficial to the response to a setpoint step.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] King describes an effective chart-based method.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Having the PID controller written in Laplace form and having the transfer function of the controlled system makes it easy to determine the closed-loop transfer function of the system.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This form essentially consists of a PD and PI controller in series.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] As the integral is required to calculate the controller's bias, this form provides the ability to track an external bias value, which is required to be used for proper implementation of multi-controller advanced control schemes.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The analysis for designing a digital implementation of a PID controller in a microcontroller (MCU) or FPGA device requires the standard form of the PID controller to be *discretized*.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Approximations for first-order derivatives are made by backward finite differences. $u(t)$ and $e(t)$ are discretized with a sampling period $\Delta t$ , k is the sample index.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] This constant is useful when you want to have a start and stop control on the regulation loop.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] For instance, setting Kp,Ki and Kd to 0 will keep u(t) constant.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Likewise, when you want to start a regulation on a system where the error is already close to 0 with u(t) non null, it prevents from sending the output to 0.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Here, `Kp` is a dimensionless number, `Ki` is expressed in s−1 and `Kd` is expressed in s.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] When doing a regulation where the actuator and the measured value are not in the same unit (e.g., temperature regulation using a motor controlling a valve), $K_{p}$ , $K_{i}$ and $K_{d}$ may be corrected by a unit conversion factor.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] It may also be interesting to use `Ki` in its reciprocal form (integration time).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The above implementation allows to perform an I-only controller which may be useful in some cases.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] In the real world, this is D-to-A converted and passed into the process under control as the manipulated variable (MV).
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] The current error is stored elsewhere for re-use in the next differentiation, the program then waits until `dt` seconds have passed since start, and the loop begins again, reading in new values for the PV and the setpoint and calculating a new value for the error.
[src:uav-flight-control/pid-controller-p02] Note that for real code, the use of `wait(dt)` might be inappropriate because it does not account for time taken by the algorithm itself during the loop, or more importantly, any pre-emption delaying the algorithm.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] The data sources for a fusion process are not specified to originate from identical sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] One can distinguish *direct fusion*, *indirect fusion* and fusion of the outputs of the former two.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Direct fusion is the fusion of sensor data from a set of heterogeneous or homogeneous sensors, soft sensors, and history values of sensor data, while indirect fusion uses information sources like *a priori* knowledge about the environment and human input.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion is also known as *(multi-sensor) data fusion* and is a subset of *information fusion*.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Two example sensor fusion calculations are illustrated below.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Let ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ denote two estimates from two independent sensor measurements, with noise variances $\scriptstyle \sigma _{1}^{2}$ and $\scriptstyle \sigma _{2}^{2}$ , respectively.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] It can be seen that the fused result is simply a linear combination of the two measurements weighted by their respective information.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] It is worth noting that if ${x}$ is a random variable.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] The estimates ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ will be correlated through common process noise, which will cause the estimate ${x}_{3}$ to lose conservativeness.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Another (equivalent) method to fuse two measurements is to use the optimal Kalman filter.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Suppose that the data is generated by a first-order system and let ${\textbf {P}}_{k}$ denote the solution of the filter's Riccati equation.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] By inspection, when the first measurement is noise free, the filter ignores the second measurement and vice versa.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] That is, the combined estimate is weighted by the quality of the measurements.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] In sensor fusion, centralized versus decentralized refers to where the fusion of the data occurs.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] In centralized fusion, the clients simply forward all of the data to a central location, and some entity at the central location is responsible for correlating and fusing the data.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] In decentralized, the clients take full responsibility for fusing the data.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Multiple combinations of centralized and decentralized systems exist.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Another classification of sensor configuration refers to the coordination of information flow between sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] These mechanisms provide a way to resolve conflicts or disagreements and to allow the development of dynamic sensing strategies.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Sensors are in redundant (or competitive) configuration if each node delivers independent measures of the same properties.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] This configuration can be used in error correction when comparing information from multiple nodes.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Redundant strategies are often used with high level fusions in voting procedures.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Complementary configuration occurs when multiple information sources supply different information about the same features.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] This strategy is used for fusing information at raw data level within decision-making algorithms.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Complementary features are typically applied in motion recognition tasks with neural network, hidden Markov model, support vector machine, clustering methods and other techniques.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor fusion uses the information extracted by multiple independent sensors to provide information that would not be available from single sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] For example, sensors connected to body segments are used for the detection of the angle between them.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor strategy gives information impossible to obtain from single nodes.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Cooperative information fusion can be used in motion recognition, gait analysis, motion analysis,,.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] There are several categories or levels of sensor fusion that are commonly used.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion level can also be defined basing on the kind of information used to feed the fusion algorithm.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] More precisely, sensor fusion can be performed fusing raw data coming from different sources, extrapolated features or even decision made by single nodes.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] One application of sensor fusion is GPS/INS, where Global Positioning System and inertial navigation system data is fused using various different methods, e.g. the extended Kalman filter.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] This is useful, for example, in determining the attitude of an aircraft using low-cost sensors.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Another example is using the data fusion approach to determine the traffic state (low traffic, traffic jam, medium flow) using road side collected acoustic, image and sensor data.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] In the field of autonomous driving, sensor fusion is used to combine the redundant information from complementary sensors in order to obtain a more accurate and reliable representation of the environment.
[src:uav-flight-control/sensor-fusion] Although technically not a dedicated sensor fusion method, modern convolutional neural network based methods can simultaneously process many channels of sensor data (such as hyperspectral imaging with hundreds of bands ) and fuse relevant information to produce classification results.
